
Java forEach loop
Java provides a new method forEach() to iterate the elements. It is defined in Iterable and Stream interface. It is a default method 
defined in the Iterable interface. Collection classes which extends Iterable interface can use forEach loop to iterate elements.

This method takes a single parameter which is a functional interface. So, you can pass lambda expression as an argument.

forEach() Signature in Iterable Interface
default void forEach(Consumer<super T>action)  
Java 8 forEach() example 1
import java.util.ArrayList;  
import java.util.List;  
public class ForEachExample {  
    public static void main(String[] args) {  
        List<String> gamesList = new ArrayList<String>();  
        gamesList.add("Football");  
        gamesList.add("Cricket");  
        gamesList.add("Chess");  
        gamesList.add("Hocky");  
        System.out.println("------------Iterating by passing lambda expression--------------");  
        gamesList.forEach(games -> System.out.println(games));  
          
    }  
} 